She's the best.

38:05.960 --> 38:08.260
So she like, we go back and forth on these things.

38:08.960 --> 38:09.840
Is she at NASA as well?

38:09.880 --> 38:10.300
She is.

38:10.540 --> 38:10.840
Wow.

38:11.080 --> 38:11.800
What'd she do there?

38:12.160 --> 38:13.680
She's in the launch services program.

38:13.860 --> 38:14.220
Cool.

38:14.360 --> 38:20.780
So she doesn't have her PhD in physics, but, um, she's taken engineering physics and undergrad

38:20.780 --> 38:22.360
and she's really good at math.

38:22.360 --> 38:25.960
So if I need help with math, I just give, Hey, Janessa, help me with this equation.

38:26.120 --> 38:27.040
Help me with this integral.

38:27.820 --> 38:29.080
She'll have like a baby on her arm.

38:29.180 --> 38:29.900
Okay, fine.

38:30.320 --> 38:31.200
I'll do it for you.

38:32.080 --> 38:32.720
That's awesome.

38:32.760 --> 38:33.960
She'll come in and look at the whiteboard.

38:34.040 --> 38:35.020
She's like, this is not right.

38:35.980 --> 38:37.140
So she's very smart.

38:37.280 --> 38:38.480
That's fun to bounce stuff off her.

38:38.480 --> 38:42.580
Um, but, uh, no, she, she was clear.

38:42.660 --> 38:46.600
She's like, no, you, you should look at this, your force that you're trying to do with his

38:46.600 --> 38:51.220
setup and see if you're working on the same thing, just a different twist as well.

38:51.240 --> 38:52.020
That can't be right.

38:52.400 --> 38:58.000
So I went back to my lab and I made a needle, but I did it differently using what I thought

38:58.000 --> 38:58.480
would work.

38:58.800 --> 39:03.640
And I would, you know, I put a, this videos of this on our website, you put a tube over

39:03.640 --> 39:06.040
the end of the needle and you put scotch tape on the tube.

39:06.520 --> 39:08.140
So there's no eye on wind getting out.

39:08.600 --> 39:10.340
And you shove the needle in that tube.

39:10.560 --> 39:11.920
You encase the darn tube.

39:12.580 --> 39:16.460
Then I cranked up my power supply and that thing moved three, four feet in the air.

39:16.960 --> 39:18.140
And I sent that video to Drew.

39:18.220 --> 39:20.980
I says, and Drew's like, oh, I guess we're working together now.

39:21.700 --> 39:22.620
Oh, wow.

39:23.620 --> 39:28.820
Um, so you have achieved how much force roughly now with your current experiments?

39:29.900 --> 39:32.440
Additives somewhere to five to 10 millinewton range.

39:32.640 --> 39:32.960
Okay.

39:32.960 --> 39:39.360
And so for people listening, if you were to apply that to like a satellite in space in

39:39.360 --> 39:43.600
a microgravity or zero gravity environment, that would be huge.

39:43.800 --> 39:44.200
Sure.

39:45.060 --> 39:46.580
You would be able to do.

39:46.860 --> 39:46.980
Yeah.

39:47.020 --> 39:47.840
Initial markets.

39:47.940 --> 39:48.860
That's what we're comfortable with.

39:48.920 --> 39:49.660
We're a space company.

39:50.300 --> 39:56.480
We all work at the space agency, different levels, not just NASA, but you know, the peripherals.

39:56.640 --> 39:58.460
And this is where we're comfortable with.

39:58.540 --> 40:02.260
There's definitely a, when we say, um, when do we hit unity?

40:02.260 --> 40:06.840
Well, we've hit unity for space, unity for moon, Mars, all of these places.

40:06.840 --> 40:10.880
So we can make flying cars on the moon and Mars and all of that.

40:11.400 --> 40:14.420
Um, so it's a very exciting place to be right now.

40:14.420 --> 40:14.880
Yep.

40:14.880 --> 40:17.640
Without any significantly huge development.

40:18.320 --> 40:20.780
It could theoretically lead to deep space exploration.

40:21.020 --> 40:21.140
Sure.

40:21.200 --> 40:26.240
You could, um, help maintain orbits for satellites where there's orbital decay.

40:26.560 --> 40:28.020
That's what our, that's what our hope is.

40:28.160 --> 40:28.260
Sure.

40:28.260 --> 40:28.460
Okay.

40:28.460 --> 40:33.620
And you can move these satellites maybe, um, to other orbits as well.

40:33.740 --> 40:36.080
Like there's a, there's a company called impulse space.

40:36.180 --> 40:40.220
They're, they're like, you know, they do like kick stages where you would move, you know,

40:40.480 --> 40:46.320
between orbits where maybe you'd go up on space X ride share with another group of satellites,

40:46.320 --> 40:48.360
but you'd want to move into a dedicated orbit.

40:48.580 --> 40:52.260
You could use a thruster like this to do something like that.

40:52.660 --> 40:53.360
No doubt.

40:53.680 --> 40:54.660
That's what our goal is.

40:55.200 --> 40:55.940
Super cool.

40:55.940 --> 40:59.600
And then what about like replacing rockets?

40:59.740 --> 41:00.960
Could we ever do that with this?

41:01.020 --> 41:03.040
Well, if we get earth unity, we don't need rockets, right?

41:03.580 --> 41:04.300
That's true.

41:04.500 --> 41:05.840
We have to think about things a little differently.

41:06.120 --> 41:06.400
Mm-hmm.

41:06.840 --> 41:11.100
But could, could the 10 million newtons of thrust turn into newtons of thrust?

41:11.680 --> 41:17.960
And could we end up launching things into space with this, you know, Exodus method or this

41:17.960 --> 41:18.920
other, this other course?

41:19.040 --> 41:20.620
That's our main goal to try to do that.

41:21.280 --> 41:24.160
You know, that's where we, the self-launchers is what we call it.

41:24.160 --> 41:26.920
Do you have blueprints around this self-launcher?

41:27.020 --> 41:27.040
No.

41:27.040 --> 41:30.120
Do you have a sense of the energy requirements or anything like that or?

41:30.340 --> 41:31.080
We don't.

41:31.200 --> 41:31.460
Okay.

41:31.600 --> 41:32.820
But we're on the path.

41:33.140 --> 41:35.000
So we know what we need to do.

41:35.100 --> 41:36.560
We just have to go set out and do it.

41:36.920 --> 41:39.340
Have you gone up in over the 2000 iterations?

41:39.540 --> 41:42.740
Have you gone up in million newtons of thrust?

41:43.040 --> 41:43.160
Sure.

41:43.540 --> 41:43.800
Okay.

41:44.440 --> 41:47.520
So you have a sense of the levers to get more thrust.

41:47.600 --> 41:48.940
There are levers and there are several.

41:49.160 --> 41:49.460
Uh-huh.

41:49.820 --> 41:51.340
And we're trying to optimize those.

41:51.500 --> 41:52.740
And what are the primary levers?

41:52.740 --> 41:55.300
There's, like we talked about voltage.

41:55.460 --> 41:55.600
Yep.

41:55.600 --> 42:01.880
The materials, properties, breakdown strength of materials, the type of signals we send,

42:02.340 --> 42:05.700
the physical limits on the materials.

42:06.640 --> 42:07.580
There's so many.

42:07.780 --> 42:11.460
What are the ideal materials for this sort of experiment?

42:11.460 --> 42:15.620
Well, we're dealing with high voltage, so we need materials with high dielectric breakdown

42:15.620 --> 42:16.040
strength.

42:16.240 --> 42:20.840
But we also have permittivity issues we have to contend with, geometry issues we have to

42:20.840 --> 42:23.640
contend with, static dissipation issues we have to contend with.

42:24.300 --> 42:26.580
There are a lot of other issues, and that's just the DC.

42:26.980 --> 42:33.160
When you get to other frequencies or you get to other exotic types, you know, charge injection,

42:33.320 --> 42:36.260
electrics, things can get even wackier.

42:36.260 --> 42:36.740
Yeah.

42:36.740 --> 42:40.800
So, we are looking at some of the interesting materials now that have other properties,

42:40.900 --> 42:42.420
which we're going to keep to ourselves for now.

42:42.620 --> 42:45.420
But it's something that's very, very interesting for now.

42:45.480 --> 42:46.420
Just to see if it goes anywhere.

42:46.580 --> 42:47.440
It could lead to nowhere.

42:47.600 --> 42:47.780
Yeah.

42:47.920 --> 42:49.260
But we're just looking at it.

42:49.600 --> 42:49.860
Cool.

42:50.140 --> 42:51.200
You know, there's other things out there.

42:51.460 --> 42:57.080
In the Townsend-Brown context, barium titanate and bismuth often come up.

42:57.160 --> 42:59.680
Are either of those relevant to your experience as well?

42:59.680 --> 43:03.920
We have some experiments with barium titanate a couple of years ago.

43:04.060 --> 43:06.900
It's a good high permittivity powder.

43:09.980 --> 43:11.800
I don't know what the results of those were.

43:11.960 --> 43:14.080
They weren't particularly interesting.

43:14.220 --> 43:15.040
What was the other one you said?

43:15.780 --> 43:16.180
Bismuth.

43:16.440 --> 43:16.980
Oh, bismuth.

43:18.080 --> 43:19.400
Yeah, I've seen bismuth a lot.

43:19.580 --> 43:20.540
Bismuth looks like fun.

43:20.900 --> 43:22.740
I would love to test with some bismuth.

43:23.060 --> 43:26.540
There's some cool things that they found, arts, parts, materials.

43:26.720 --> 43:26.900
Yep.

43:26.900 --> 43:32.120
Which is kind of neat because they had some weird geometries in there, which I would project that we would have needed.

43:32.600 --> 43:36.520
But to see that in real life already made, I was like, oh, that's kind of cool.

43:37.960 --> 43:41.500
I can't wait to go test those exotics, but that's down the road for us.

43:41.640 --> 43:41.860
Yep.

43:42.100 --> 43:48.260
We're going to try to stay focused and do what we're good at right now and then work on the more exotic stuff later, I think.

43:48.260 --> 43:54.240
And so in doing these experiments, did you have access to a vacuum chamber?

43:54.360 --> 43:59.460
Because I feel like it's been a lot of – the reason – you know, everybody always questions me on this.

43:59.540 --> 44:03.600
They're like, this experiment sounds very simple because I always bring up the Townsend-Brown experiment.

44:04.260 --> 44:05.900
And they're like, why has nobody done it yet?

44:05.900 --> 44:08.840
And I say – I give two reasons.

44:08.980 --> 44:13.160
I say people always try to explain it away via the ion wind.

44:13.860 --> 44:18.820
And it's so similar to the ion wind-related experiments that it's easy to do that.

44:18.880 --> 44:21.960
It's always easy to say there's ambient ionization in the vacuum.

44:22.520 --> 44:23.320
That's number one.

44:23.380 --> 44:28.100
And then number two, access to an industrial-grade vacuum chamber is pretty limited.

44:28.100 --> 44:29.980
And it's obviously very expensive.

44:30.300 --> 44:35.540
And so did you have access, you know, based on your kind of NASA background?

44:36.760 --> 44:37.200
Yes.

44:37.660 --> 44:39.620
You know, Drew and I have access to a chamber.

44:39.740 --> 44:40.840
He's got one at his house.

44:41.400 --> 44:42.780
He's very resourceful.

44:43.040 --> 44:43.380
Amazing.

44:43.520 --> 44:44.560
He funded it himself.

44:44.900 --> 44:46.760
It's a nice-sized vacuum chamber.

44:47.040 --> 44:53.120
He also has a second one that he's going to get online soon, which is almost a walk-in-sized vacuum chamber.

44:53.120 --> 44:59.440
So, very pricey, but hopefully with some funding we can get that thing up to par and running.

45:00.640 --> 45:02.960
But yes, we do have access to a high vacuum chamber.

45:03.060 --> 45:04.400
That's where we do most of our tests.

45:05.000 --> 45:10.400
And let's describe to the audience why it's important that ion wind can't get out.

45:10.520 --> 45:14.820
Because this is how, you know, I learned about all this stuff through Thomas Townsend Brown.

45:15.420 --> 45:17.880
And he used to do these experiments.

45:17.880 --> 45:25.840
So, Thomas Townsend Brown, this super interesting, mysterious guy who pops up at extremely high levels of aerospace.

45:26.220 --> 45:27.920
He was at the Navy for a very long time.

45:28.020 --> 45:33.160
He was at Martin Corporation the year that Skunk Works was formed in 1942 or 3.

45:34.620 --> 45:44.340
There's an FBI document that is circulated now and out about him and says that he's the lead radar scientist in the entire Navy.

45:44.420 --> 45:46.480
He knows more about radar than anybody in the Navy.

45:46.480 --> 45:57.220
We have a lot of evidence that his electrohydrodynamics work, you know, this electric fields to manipulate airflow work, ended up in the B-2 stealth bomber.

45:57.580 --> 46:02.860
So, you have like two out of three things that he's talking about definitely being legit.

46:03.120 --> 46:07.580
And then the third thing he's saying is I've merged electromagnetism and gravity.

46:07.580 --> 46:09.300
And he talks about electrogravitics.

46:09.440 --> 46:20.100
And it's specifically two experiments, 1956 in Paris, of which we have a witness who there's an audio recording of a deathbed confession in 2009.

46:20.240 --> 46:27.820
This guy, Jacques Corneone, who's a technical consultant for Sued West, which is, you know, an aerospace corporation there.

46:27.820 --> 46:41.700
And, you know, they say there is a force that is not only measurable in a vacuum at 10 to the negative 6 torr, but the force exceeds what you would ever see outside of a vacuum.

46:41.700 --> 46:46.500
And then he does the same experiment at the Bonson Labs, the Institute of Field Physics in North Carolina.

46:47.340 --> 46:52.620
And it's this remarkable thing where you have this guy, two out of the three things he's saying, probably right.

46:53.000 --> 46:58.060
You have, you know, he's dealing with Curtis LeMay and the Rand Corporation, all these super high up people.

46:58.060 --> 47:04.800
And then this electrogravitics thing just gets stigmatized and people just kind of forget about it.

47:04.920 --> 47:10.860
And it almost feels like he's trying to he has this wounded prairie chicken routine where he's trying to stigmatize his own work.

47:11.360 --> 47:13.480
And so it's fascinating.

47:14.140 --> 47:18.760
And the reason so this is very long winded, but you mentioned ion wind.

47:18.760 --> 47:32.560
The way people write off any of these experiments, including Thomas Townsend Brown's, is they say that these capacitor experiments, especially if they take place not in a vacuum, you end up with ionized air.

47:32.560 --> 47:41.280
The ionized air then bounces off of other air particles and it's basically just Newton's law taking place and then you get thrust.

47:41.280 --> 47:49.580
And so that's very different than showing this in a vacuum chamber or in this case, you mitigated ions in another way.

47:49.660 --> 47:50.080
Is that right?

47:51.300 --> 47:52.200
Well, you kind of have to.

47:52.400 --> 47:52.480
Yeah.

47:52.520 --> 47:54.640
Otherwise, you'll see the ion wind thrust.

47:54.880 --> 47:58.780
So you can either cap it, enclose it in a volume, whatever you have to do.

47:59.440 --> 48:01.940
But you don't want the ion wind to be playing a role here.

48:02.180 --> 48:02.400
Yep.

48:03.400 --> 48:07.880
And one of the things that's different about the force that we're talking about in the ion wind force,

48:07.880 --> 48:12.480
at least in terms of geometry, is that the devices will move with the wind.

48:12.980 --> 48:15.360
So imagine a rocket moving in the direction that the exhaust is.

48:15.760 --> 48:16.480
That's crazy.

48:17.120 --> 48:21.080
So you have to remove the ion wind because of the stigma from it.

48:21.220 --> 48:21.400
Yep.

48:21.400 --> 48:27.440
Because a lot of scientists have tried to do these things and they've seen the ion wind and it's not a real force in the sense.

48:27.860 --> 48:29.920
It's not a propellant-less force.

48:30.320 --> 48:31.860
There's propellant there, the wind.

48:32.040 --> 48:32.240
Yep.

48:32.840 --> 48:34.460
But the other thing is not.

48:34.540 --> 48:35.360
That's a different thing.

48:35.680 --> 48:35.960
Yeah.

48:36.140 --> 48:37.640
That's a completely different beast.

48:37.880 --> 48:42.580
And you would be an authority in your ability to delineate between-

48:42.580 --> 48:42.860
Sure.

48:43.020 --> 48:49.260
I do videos where I take the lifters and I put them in a plastic box and put it on a scale.

48:49.740 --> 48:50.000
Yeah.

48:50.240 --> 48:51.640
And you watch the weight.

48:52.360 --> 48:56.180
And you turn it on, the thing lifts up and the weight's flat lines does not move at all.

48:56.360 --> 48:56.720
Wow.

48:56.720 --> 48:59.220
So Drew was like, man, I've never seen that video before.

48:59.300 --> 49:00.840
That's conservation momentum right there.

49:01.340 --> 49:02.800
That's what ion wind is doing.

49:02.980 --> 49:03.160
Yep.

49:03.160 --> 49:15.540
So that's exactly like, you have all these DIY videos of these balsa wood lifters with tin foil and you have the ions moving around the copper coil or whatever, and then you end up with thrust.

49:15.540 --> 49:27.700
But that is not this electrogravitic force or what you are calling this exodus force or electrostatic variation force, whatever it is.

49:27.700 --> 49:28.700
That is different.

49:28.840 --> 49:30.240
That is another force.

49:30.840 --> 49:35.760
So it's important for any experimental physicists who want to pour cold water on this.

49:36.040 --> 49:46.760
And the funny thing is Brown himself would use the electrohydrodynamic stuff, the stuff involving ion wind, to cover for the electrogravitics.

49:46.760 --> 49:52.400
He would literally like, because it's 95% similar, but it's not the same thing.

49:52.480 --> 49:59.080
And again, you are in a kind of an authoritative position in order to, you know, you have the ability to delineate between those two things.

49:59.500 --> 50:00.180
Yeah, that's important.

50:00.680 --> 50:01.860
It is really important.

50:02.000 --> 50:02.200
Yeah.

50:02.640 --> 50:08.020
And it's, yeah, it's important because it's always the first order debunk on this entire thing.

50:08.420 --> 50:13.060
So you do this experiment that eliminates or controls for ion wind.

50:13.060 --> 50:22.020
And I'm assuming you, since then, have done a series of experiments to control for all sorts of other possible confounding variables.

50:23.120 --> 50:23.640
Yes.

50:24.040 --> 50:30.780
So after Drew and I did these experiments in 2016, I think we spent about two years trying to package it.

50:31.320 --> 50:35.560
Now, there's one thing to put 100,000 volts on a device and have it move around in the room.

50:36.800 --> 50:38.660
Drew and I both knew that was completely impractical.

50:38.660 --> 50:45.280
You can't do anything with that because you have to make something to attach it to a vehicle, to a rocket, to something that people have to be around.

50:46.440 --> 50:49.360
And this, this better damn well go inside of grounded box.

50:49.740 --> 50:52.360
So we made a lot of effort.

50:52.480 --> 50:58.200
It took a lot of effort those two years to get the sucker packaged up in a way so it can actually be transportable and confined.

50:58.200 --> 51:07.800
And so that was the initial pull to go into, to get into a system where we can actually enclose everything.

51:08.460 --> 51:11.640
Coolant forces are the biggest killer in vacuum or in air.

51:11.940 --> 51:14.900
So you can, you know, you can apply high voltage to something.

51:15.040 --> 51:17.680
It'll attract to the wall, floors, ceilings far away.

51:17.800 --> 51:18.680
It can still do that.

51:18.680 --> 51:23.900
So you have to make sure that everything you do is inside a very well-grounded Faraday cage.

51:24.480 --> 51:29.580
So that is another one of our, our tests, our checks and balances.

51:30.220 --> 51:32.240
You know, do we have it inside of a Faraday cage?

51:32.440 --> 51:33.540
Is it all completely housed?

51:33.640 --> 51:35.380
Is it feels trapped within the system?

51:35.940 --> 51:37.180
Do we spin it the other way?

51:37.220 --> 51:40.460
There's a lot of checks and balances that we have to do along the, along the, along the way.

51:41.120 --> 51:44.020
So Faraday cage would eliminate magnetic field interference?

51:44.440 --> 51:44.760
No.

51:45.160 --> 51:45.480
Okay.

51:45.920 --> 51:46.780
Only electric field.

51:46.780 --> 51:48.180
Only electric field interference.

51:48.680 --> 51:54.100
And then you also need vacuum chamber because, is that right or no?

51:54.320 --> 51:55.420
You don't need it.

51:55.480 --> 51:56.320
It's a lot easier.

51:56.560 --> 51:56.800
Okay.

51:56.920 --> 51:57.880
Because you get rid of the air.

51:58.260 --> 52:02.160
The gas breaks down like a million volts per meter fields.

52:02.540 --> 52:03.820
So the gases start breaking down.

52:04.020 --> 52:05.920
And when they break down, they create their own charges.

52:06.200 --> 52:09.780
And when they create their own charges, you can put charges where you don't want it.

52:09.960 --> 52:13.500
You can short, you can have charges leaking around the side.

52:13.860 --> 52:15.180
It really messes with you.

52:15.180 --> 52:19.200
So to do things in air is a bit more complicated than vacuum.

52:19.280 --> 52:20.300
Vacuum, you don't have to worry about that.

52:20.500 --> 52:22.140
Moisture is the biggest killer, especially in Florida.

52:22.140 --> 52:26.460
So you want to do stuff in a very dry environment or high vacuum if you can.

52:26.460 --> 52:29.480
So you're saying that in a vacuum chamber, you get more thrust.

52:29.660 --> 52:31.900
You could make a system work better.

52:32.400 --> 52:32.640
Yes.

52:32.740 --> 52:33.020
Interesting.

52:33.420 --> 52:36.660
Well, that's Townsend Brown also said you'd get more thrust.

52:36.920 --> 52:40.420
You get more thrust because the field limit is not 10 to the sixth anymore.

52:40.540 --> 52:41.220
It's 10 to the eighth.

52:41.480 --> 52:41.800
Right.

52:41.800 --> 52:45.840
So that's because it goes, the forces are related to pressure.

52:45.960 --> 52:47.460
They go up by field squared.

52:47.800 --> 52:53.260
So instead of 10 to the sixth squared is 10 to the twelfth, 10 to the eighth squared is 10 to the 16.

52:53.580 --> 53:01.740
So now you have four orders of magnitude potential higher thrust just on the exterior part of your thrusters.

53:02.840 --> 53:05.160
So there's more to draw from the field.

53:05.640 --> 53:06.180
That's right.

53:06.500 --> 53:07.400
This is a field effect.

53:07.480 --> 53:08.340
It's not a voltage effect.

53:09.340 --> 53:10.320
It's fascinating.

53:10.740 --> 53:10.920
Yeah.

53:11.040 --> 53:11.960
It's so interesting.

53:12.280 --> 53:21.380
But it really flies in the face of the debunkers saying that it's attributable to ion wind because in an environment where there is less ion wind, you are getting more thrust.

53:21.380 --> 53:28.120
And it might be due to this field effect, but still, you're controlling for the ion wind, which is what they're saying is accounting for the thrust.

53:28.820 --> 53:28.840
Yes.

53:28.920 --> 53:35.220
And you have to also, when you're in a vacuum chamber, now you have a new falsity, which could be the walls of the vacuum chamber, giant metal ground.

53:35.220 --> 53:43.600
So you want to make sure that you put your test device, whatever it is, in the side of a Faraday cage, and then you measure the force on the Faraday cage, nothing else.

53:43.720 --> 53:44.580
Not what's inside of it.

